      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1659">
               <p>Pritchard was a native of <placeName>County Meath, Ireland</placeName>. About
                     <date when="1765">1765</date> he came to <placeName>London</placeName>, where
                  he was drawn into Wesleyan circles and converted. <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> appointed him as class leader
                  over a group of young men. While their enthusiasm raised concern among some,
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> saw potential
                  and in <date when="1770-03">March 1770</date> asked Pritchard to accompany him on
                  his preaching tour of <placeName>Ireland</placeName>. On their return
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> convinced
                  Pritchard to go study at Kingswood School and in late <date when="1771"
                     >1771</date>
                  <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> sent Pritchard to
                  preach on the <placeName>Wiltshire</placeName> circuit. Pritchard was formally
                  accepted by the <date when="1772">1772</date> Conference as a <seg
                     ana="itinerancy">traveling preacher</seg> (see <hi rend="italic">Works</hi>,
                  10:405). His first year under appointment was rocky, but he found his feet and
                     <seg ana="itinerancy">itinerated</seg> for thirty years. In <date when="1802"
                     >1802</date> he was asked by Conference to serve as Governor of Kingswood
                  School, which he did for five years. See <hi rend="italic">EMP</hi>, 6:249–72; and
                     <hi rend="italic">Minutes</hi> (post- Wesley, <date when="1814">1814</date>),
                  4:6.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
